<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Statistics and Open Data: Evidence from Dr</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 17.85pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Statistics and Open Data: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rom </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dr. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ben Worthy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> [OD003]</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Dr Ben Worthy is a Lecturer in Politics at Birkbeck College, University of London. His research interests include Transparency, Freedom of Information and Open Data. </span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">current </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strategy lacks clarity, moving between economic and democratic objectives. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Focusing on the publication of local government spending data, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">research indicates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use of the data is low, due to a combination of technical and political obstacles. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The biggest users appear to be business and NGOs. There is unlikely to be an ‘Army’ of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Armchair Auditors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but more a mix of journalists, NGOs and activists working in particular circumstances.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Being localised and small scale Open Data has the potential to be a pow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">erful tool. Contextualising, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">joining up data and linking it to other participatory mechanisms will help realise its potential but barriers remain high. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Research and Methods</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following findings are based on a piece of on-going research on the impact of the Coalition’s Transparency Agenda since 2010. The research focuses on local government, particularly the publication of all spending over £500. It is based on a survey of local authorities, FOI requests </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">selected authorities, and interviews with practitioners, innovators and users.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As of writing (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">28</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">August 2013) the information is not compl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ete. The survey currently has 54 r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">esponses representing around 15</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">% of local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The FOI requests were made to 50 authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The data below needs to be read with these limitations in mind. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There is also some inconsistency among responses, between for example hits or visits.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on-going</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, all findings are provisional. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why is Open Data important? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Open Data offers an opportunity for a number of groups. For the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, as well as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> journalists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> NGOs,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Open Data offers the chance to make government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> more transparent and open. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also may work to increase levels of public trust or participation, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">though these are complex areas where information can have uncertain and unpredictable effects.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It offers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">innovators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the chance to re-use data for political, economic and social applications. These can go from the democratic (such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Openly Local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) to the everyday (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">school finder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). Such innovations are likely to be vital bridges to wider public use and access. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> themselves, it offers the chance to be more responsive by, for example, strengthening the evidence base of policy-making or targeting resources in a particular direction. To fully realise this would require joining up and sharing data, something many authorities appear keen on but at present feel they lack the resources to do.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One important point to make is that Open Data is not Freedom of Information, though the two overlap. While FOI is about accessing information, Open Data is also about re-use, innovation and adaption. Seeing one as a replacement for the other risks obscuring these key differences. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For Open Data, the mix of technology and political aims further confuses the meaning. One recent study spoke of how the definition itself is ‘deeply ambiguous’ as it ‘blurred the distinction between the technology of Open Data and the politics of Open Government’. </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why does the Government need an open data strategy? What should the Government’s aims be for the release of open data? Are the Government’s stated key outcomes in its Open Data Strategy the right ones? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The core of Open Data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reform concerns publishing ‘government data in a reusable form’.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One emerging issue is the lack of clarity over the exact aims of the government’s Transparency Agenda.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> A number of interviewees spoke of how government emphasis shifts between the ‘democratic’ aspects, using data to improve public understanding and participation, to the ‘economic’ objectives, creating re-use and economic growth. As the Shakespeare review pointed out, these aims may contradict each other and lead to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">different areas of government ‘pushing’ different aims.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is likely to be further complicated by the competing economic aims of the EU P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ublic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nformation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> agenda</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some of the aims are also hedged with uncertainty. The NAO felt that the economic aims were based on ‘highly uncertain assumptions’ and a number of interviewees felt similarly that, while the potential was clearly there, economic aims may be difficult to realise.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Other ideas, such as the concept of the ‘Armchair Auditors’, may also not work in the manner hoped (see below). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This lack of clarity is reflected in confusion among public bodies. A 2012 survey of by the LGA found a lack of understanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at local level over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who Open Data was intended for and concern that there was no clear strategy behind it.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is open data presented well and of adequate quality? Are the formats of the data being published accessible, useable and understandable to the public? What metadata is needed to make releases useful? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Public Accounts Committee (2012) highlighted concerns over how data was inconsistent, ‘raw’ and ‘very difficult to interpret’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This was for two reasons. First, information needed to be comparable across equivalent bodies. Current use of excel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">files </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with short descriptors prevented any rigorous measurement between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Second, information needed to be contextualised and accompanied by some form of ‘narrative’. One concern is that presentation ‘frames’ interpretation. So, for example, publication of spending data lends itself to consideration of ‘waste’ and ‘spending’ rather than understanding the effect the money has.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> A fully ‘joined up’ approach could trace spending from central government down to local authority and then to the impact. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Third, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">spending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> information fits with the ‘granular’ and small-scale approach associated with successful online democracy experiments.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However, to bring about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">real accountability and participation the data also needs to be linked to clear and functioning accountability mechanisms. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Who will use the Data?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">FOI requests were made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to selected authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for the numbers of views of spending pages. There was variability in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">number of visits (which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> also recorded differently). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Below are a few examples</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, chosen simply to illustrate the variety.</span></p><div style="text-align:center"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin:0 auto"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:90.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> type</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:113.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Number of</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">page</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">views </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Jan-Dec 2012</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:90.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">district</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; p